    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2271524916" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2271524916" />
    <a title="Mutasim Billah " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/20438238-mutasim-billah"><img alt="Mutasim Billah " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1536682441p2/20438238.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2271524916?book_show_action=true">Apr 19, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mutasim Billah " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mutasim Billah " href="/user/show/20438238-mutasim-billah">Mutasim Billah </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781408842423" href="/book/show/17345741-and-the-mountains-echoed">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20438238-mutasim-billah?shelf=afghanistan">afghanistan</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2271524916" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12978979324095888219"><blockquote>
  <i>“They say, Find a purpose in your life and live it. But, sometimes, it is only after you have lived that you recognize your life had a purpose, and likely one you never had in mind.”</i>
</blockquote><br/><br/>A story spanning generations and across continents, <i>And the Mountains Echoed</i> is a brilliant example of storytelling. There can only be so many stories of so many people spanning differences in culture and class, painting images of poverty, war, love, compassion, hatred and longing that you start to wonder if a wo</span>
  <span id="freeText12978979324095888219" style="display:none"><blockquote>
  <i>“They say, Find a purpose in your life and live it. But, sometimes, it is only after you have lived that you recognize your life had a purpose, and likely one you never had in mind.”</i>
</blockquote><br><br>A story spanning generations and across continents, <i>And the Mountains Echoed</i> is a brilliant example of storytelling. There can only be so many stories of so many people spanning differences in culture and class, painting images of poverty, war, love, compassion, hatred and longing that you start to wonder if a world could be more at odds sometimes among its own inhabitants.<br><br>At the center of this tale that begins in 1952, we have Abdullah and Pari, brother and sister who are suddenly estranged due to a decision made by their father under extreme poverty. The story is significantly inspired by the father beginning a story at the request of his children, about a poor parent that has to let go of his beloved child. Throughout the book, multiple stories align such that this story gets a purposeful ending.<br>
  <br>
  <img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1591465746i/29604797._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
  <br>
  
    <i>“All good things in life are fragile and easily lost.” Image: Kabul, 1977</i>
  
  <br>
<br>The story touches up on multiple subjects, like the treatment of women in Afghan society and the significant gap in respect and compassion that is shown to them based on their class and stature in society. The Soviet-Afghan war plays a significant part, and the stories of Afghan refugees as a result of subsequent conflict in the region over the years also makes up most of the story.<br>
  <br>
  <img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1591465019i/29604763._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
  <br>
  
    <i>"When you have lived as long as I have, the div replied, you find that cruelty and benevolence are but shades of the same color."</i>
  
  <br>
<br>The problem, however, with the subsequent resulting book is too many sub-plots unrelated to the core of the story. Some of these appear completely unrelated and could be individual stories of their own. However, the overall desired effect of the book hits home in the end as an emotional roller-coaster ride.<br><br><blockquote>
  <i>“A story is like a moving train: no matter where you hop onboard, you are bound to reach your destination sooner or later.”</i>
</blockquote></span>
  <a data-text-id="12978979324095888219" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

